properties.theme_explanation_summary: The city evokes envy for a perceived identical past happiness_ highlighting memory's elusive nature.
The city of youthful desires is reached in old age_ transforming those desires into memories.
Dorothea's reality depends on the observer's approach_ shaping understanding through structure or experience.
The city's physical form is intrinsically defined by and contains its past relationships and events.
The city's promise of total desire satisfaction paradoxically results in inhabitants' complete enslavement to it.
Tamara's identity is constructed through layers of signs_ obscuring its true nature beneath imposed interpretation.
Zora's rigid structure_ designed for perfect memorability_ paradoxically leads to its stasis and eventual oblivion.
Despina's form is perceived dually_ shaped by the contrasting desires of desert-opposed travelers approaching it.
Zirma achieves existence through redundant signs that imprint varied_ yet characteristic_ memories on its travelers.
Isaura's visible upward structure and dualistic beliefs are conditioned by its hidden subterranean lake.
Maurilia explores the disconnection between past and present cities sharing a name_ questioning authentic nostalgia.
Fedora's museum of miniature ideal cities embodies unfulfilled desires and potentials_ existing as mere assumptions.
Zoe's lack of internal differentiation challenges the mind's tendency to impose order and categories.
Zenobia embodies happiness not by a fixed state_ but by its continuous adaptation to desires.
In Euphemia_ memories are traded and transformed like goods_ altering personal histories through shared narratives.
Zobeide is built from a shared dream of chasing an elusive woman_ becoming a trap itself.
Hypatia subverts expected meanings of signs_ forcing reinterpretation and acknowledging language's inherent deceit.
Armilla's skeletal structure of pipes_ devoid of human habitation_ becomes a realm for mythical water spirits.
Chloe thrives on the unspoken_ imagined interactions between strangers_ maintaining a chaste surface over seething fantasies.
Valdrada's mirrored existence forces acute self-awareness_ yet the city and its reflection lack true connection.
Olivia reveals that words can describe opposing realities; true falsehood lies not in words_ but in things.
Sophronia's dual nature_ one fixed_ one mobile_ illustrates a cyclical quest for temporary completeness.
Eutropia offers constant renewal by shifting inhabitants between identical cities_ yet the overall existence remains static.
Zemrude's perceived form changes with the observer's mood and gaze_ often leading to a downward focus.
Aglaura exists more in its storied reputation than its physical presence_ as language fails to capture its true essence.
Octavia's existence suspended over an abyss on a finite net highlights life's inherent precariousness.
Ersilia defines itself by abstract relationship strings_ leaving behind skeletal forms when inhabitants relocate.
Baucis_ elevated and unseen_ reflects on its inhabitants' detached relationship with the earth below.
Leandra's essence is debated by its dual household gods_ representing conflicting views on tradition and change.
Melania's life is a continuous play where actors change but roles persist_ showing societal scripts.
Esmeralda's multi-layered network of routes offers infinite unrePEated paths_ reflecting life's complex choices.
Phyllis initially delights with varied details_ but prolonged stay reduces it to internalized_ subjective routes.
Pyrrha's reality overwrites its imagined form_ highlighting how names anchor perception_ yet many imagined cities remain.
In Adelma_ travelers see faces of their dead in the living_ suggesting arrival means joining them.
Eudoxia's true ordered form_ hidden beneath its chaos_ is revealed in its carpet_ a map mirroring cosmic order or vice-versa.
Moriana presents a beautiful facade and a hidden decaying obverse_ like a two-sided sheet_ inseparable yet distinct.
Clarice's history of decay and renewal shows how a city's splendor is fragmented_ reordered_ and reinterpreted over time.
Eusapia's living city copies its dead counterpart_ which itself innovates_ blurring who influences whom and who is truly alive.
Beersheba misinterprets its celestial (waste) and infernal (perfection) projections_ true virtue found in generous abandon.
Leonia's obsession with daily newness creates an ever-expanding fortress of its own discarded past.
Irene's identity is tied to distant observation; it changes upon approach_ a name for an elusive concept.
Argia's substitution of earth for air signifies a buried_ unseen existence_ suggesting an oppressive or dead city.
Thekla's endless construction aims to prevent destruction_ its ultimate blueprint revealed only in the stars.
Trude represents a world covered by a single_ endlessly repeating city_ where only superficial names differ.
Olinda grows concentrically_ with new cities emerging from its core_ maintaining features of its origin.
Laudomia exists as three interconnected cities (living_ dead_ unborn)_ reflecting on legacy_ continuity_ and temporality's anxieties.
Perinthia's perfect astronomical design results in a city of monsters_ questioning divine order or human calculation.
Procopia's landscape is gradually obscured by an ever-increasing_ yet polite_ population within a confined view.
Raissa_ city of sadness_ unknowingly contains moments of happiness linked by an invisible thread of interconnected lives.
Andria's perfect celestial order is not static; city innovations cause corresponding changes in the sky.
Cecilia becomes everywhere and nowhere_ as distinctions between city and non-city_ or specific locations_ dissolve through perspective.
Marozia embodies two states_ oppressive (rat) and liberated (swallow)_ with the latter struggling to emerge from the former.
Penthesilea's sprawling_ undefined form blurs city and periphery_ questioning if an 'outside' or distinct 'inside' exists.
Theodora_ after eradicating all animal life_ faces the resurgence of forgotten mythological fauna_ challenging its human-centric order.
Berenice comprises intertwined cities of just and unjust_ each containing the seed of the other_ in a complex temporal succession.
